    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I'm working on an embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU and we're seeing a slow memory leak. It's not crashing immediately, but the heap is slowly exhausting over a 4-hour period. \n\nHere is a simplified version of the telemetry processing loop where we suspect the issue is:\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_sensor_data(const SensorPacket* packet) {\n    if (packet->status == VALID) {\n        DataBuffer* buffer = new DataBuffer(packet->payload_size);\n        buffer->copy_from(packet->payload);\n        \n        // Add to the processing queue\n        m_queue.push_back(buffer);\n    }\n    \n    // Update metrics\n    m_metrics.total_packets_processed++;\n}\n\nvoid maintenance_cycle() {\n    // Periodically try to clear old data\n    auto it = m_queue.begin();\n    while (it != m_queue.end()) {\n        if ((*it)->is_expired()) {\n            // System should free memory here\n            it = m_queue.erase(it);\n        } else {\n            ++it;\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nCan you give me a systematic way to debug this? I can't use heavy tools like Valgrind on the actual hardware due to resource constraints.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A memory leak in an embedded system without heavy tools requires a careful, methodical approach. First, you must ensure that every time you call `new DataBuffer`, there is a corresponding `delete` call when the buffer is finished. Since you are using `m_queue.erase(it)`, the manual deletion is likely missing inside `maintenance_cycle()`.\n\nYou should iterate through the queue in `maintenance_cycle()`, and for every item you erase, you must explicitly call `delete` on that pointer before advancing the iterator. If the leak persists, consider replacing raw pointers and `new`/`delete` with smart pointers like `std::unique_ptr` if your compiler supports it, as this automates cleanup. This eliminates the need for manual memory management, which is often the source of leaks.",
      "source": "target",
