    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, I'll check the manual deletion in the erase loop. I'll also try moving to unique_ptr if the toolchain allows it. \n\nOne thing though: even after fixing the explicit delete, we're still seeing some minor, irregular jumps in heap usage that don't quite match the steady leak. It's like small chunks of memory are disappearing at random intervals rather than in a constant linear progression. How do I track down those more intermittent, \"hidden\" issues where the cause isn't immediately obvious in the main logic?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Intermittent heap usage jumps, especially when they aren't a steady leak, often point to subtle resource management issues or fragmentation, not just simple leaks. You need to monitor the *allocation* and *deallocation* patterns, not just the final usage.\n\nIf you cannot use Valgrind, you might be able to implement a very lightweight, custom heap tracking mechanism. This involves wrapping your `new` and `delete` operators (or the functions that call them) to log every allocation size and address to a small, dedicated ring buffer in persistent RAM. When the usage jumps, you can review the last few logged transactions to see if a small, unexpected allocation is occurring and never being paired with a deallocation. This is much lighter than a full heap checker and should reveal the rogue calls.",
      "source": "target",
