    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "The ring buffer idea is good, but the jumps are hard to pin down because they seem to happen in the background, almost like they aren't part of the main execution flow. It's very frustrating because everything looks correct on the surface, but there's always this sense that something is \"sneaking\" in and taking memory behind my back.\n\nAre there any other patterns or common culprits I should look for? Specifically, are there ways these tiny, non-linear memory thefts happen in embedded systems that aren't just simple \"forgetting to delete\" errors?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When memory seems to be \"sneaking\" in without a clear allocation trace, you must look beyond the application logic and consider the environment itself. A common culprit in embedded systems is the use of global or static data structures that are being re-initialized or resized unexpectedly during background tasks, which can trigger hidden allocations.\n\nAnother possibility is dynamic memory usage within libraries or hardware abstraction layers (HALs) that you aren't fully controlling; perhaps a driver re-buffers data internally during interrupts or DMA transfers. Check any code that runs asynchronously or in ISRs, as these often have different memory safety guarantees than your main loop. If you suspect fragmentation is causing the jumps, try running the system with a fixed-size allocation pool allocator instead of the system heap.",
      "source": "target",
